            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by Grashnak:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by newwb:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by sep332:<BR>This can't possibly be an issue of recouping costs for the RIAA.  It's not like they were ever going to see $1.9MM out of her.  It's totally a deterrent, which is why I believe the RIAA will go back for another full trial instead of accepting the $54,000. </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Wouldn't that be double jeopardy? </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>Um, no.  If they choose to ask for a new trial, then this trial gets set aside and it's a new trial on the same complaint.  Double jeopardy prevents you from being punished twice, not from multiple trials in a case where there are mistrials etc. </div></BLOCKQUOTE>You're both wrong.  The "double jeopardy" rule protects you from being tried for the same <I>crime</I> twice; this was a civil trial, not a criminal, so double jeopardy rules do not apply.<BR><BR>Remember how OJ Simpson got tried twice?  The first time was criminal; the second was civil.  The standards for civil trials are MUCH plaintiff-friendlier than the standards for criminal trials - and both defendant AND plaintiff may appeal a verdict or judgment to the next highest court in the circuit, all the way up the chain until either both are satisfied, or the next court up denies the appeal.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
